Dickens' Village
Revised 10/29/2022

Dickens' Village is a porcelain collection that falls under and was the cornerstone of the Heritage Village Collection umbrella. Dicken's Village was originally designed by Neilan Lund. His inspiration derived from Victorian London during the time of well-known artist Charles Dickens. Many Dickensian works were offered as subseries' in the early years along with his most popular one- A Christmas Carol. The collection is so true to the times that you can almost hear the clattering of carriages over the cobble streets in retailer and collector displays.

The original set of seven buildings were offered as a set of seven with one SKU. Lore has it that the Candle Shop was an after-thought when upon review the original buildings comprised of a butcher and a baker but no candle stick maker.

It should also be noted that the Coordinating Accessories Carolers (s/3) had numerous mold and painting variations which was not uncommon in some of the early year designs for Dickens' Village.

Dickens' Village is where you will find the largest collection of subseries' including not only A Christmas Carol, Dickens' Market, twelfth Night, numerous inns, Manor Homes, and Gaslight Pubs. As mentioned above, David Copperfield, Nicholas Nickleby and Oliver twist are just some of Dickens' popular works that are also included.

The Dickens' Village series was released in 1984 and designated as part of the Heritage Village Collection due to its porcelain makeup. The original set of seven buildings were designed by Neilan Lund and were also released under one pre-pack SKU number (65153). The inspiration for the collection was Victorian London during the times of Charles Dickens.

The Coordinating Accessories Carolers (s/3) was the only accessories introduced the same year. There are three variations of the set. The first issue contains a man leaning against a bare porcelain post facing the opposite direction of the latter two issues.
